    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do women need different probiotics than men?</summary>
      <p>Women have a vaginal microbiome dominated by Lactobacillus species that maintains acidic pH (3.8-4.5) to prevent infections. Specific strains like L. rhamnosus GR-1 and L. reuteri RC-14 colonize vaginal mucosa when taken orally via the gut-vaginal axis. General probiotics lack these women-specific strains.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can probiotics help prevent UTIs?</summary>
      <p>Yes. L. rhamnosus GR-1 and L. reuteri RC-14 reduced UTI recurrence by 73% in clinical trials by colonizing the vaginal tract and producing hydrogen peroxide and lactic acid that kill E. coli. The gut-vaginal axis allows oral probiotics to modify vaginal flora.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many CFU do women need in a probiotic?</summary>
      <p>Strain specificity matters more than CFU count. 1 billion CFU of a clinically studied vaginal strain is more effective than 50 billion of a generic strain. For general digestive health, 5-10 billion CFU is standard. For vaginal health, L. rhamnosus GR-1 + L. reuteri RC-14 at 1-2 billion CFU each has the strongest evidence.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do probiotic gummies survive stomach acid?</summary>
      <p>Some strains are naturally acid-resistant (L. rhamnosus, Bacillus coagulans) and survive gastric transit without enteric coating. Other strains experience die-off. Quality gummy formulas use acid-resistant strains and may over-dose CFU to account for gastric losses. Look for "guaranteed at expiration" CFU claims.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can probiotics help with yeast infections?</summary>
      <p>Specific Lactobacillus strains prevent yeast infections by maintaining acidic vaginal pH that inhibits Candida. A 2009 study found L. rhamnosus GR-1 + L. reuteri RC-14 significantly reduced yeast infection episodes over 12 months. Probiotics are preventive, not curative — active infections require antifungal treatment first.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take probiotics during antibiotic treatment?</summary>
      <p>Yes, spaced 2-3 hours from antibiotic doses. A 2012 Cochrane meta-analysis found probiotics reduced antibiotic-associated diarrhea by 42%. Continue for 2-4 weeks after completing the antibiotic course. Saccharomyces boulardii (a probiotic yeast) is particularly effective during antibiotics.</p>
    </details>

